The paper discusses the evaluation of incomplete satisfiability solvers, which is a topic related to artificial intelligence and machine learning (cs.AI). The paper also introduces a new model for generating hard satisfiable instances of k-SAT formulas, which involves the geometry of the space of satisfying truth assignments, suggesting a connection to computational geometry and topology (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the effects of different algorithms on the satisfiability of the formulas, which is a topic related to computational complexity (cs.CC). Additionally, the paper presents theoretical and experimental evidence to support its claims, which suggests a connection to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and machine learning (cs.LG).
